ON THIS DAY... 34 years ago, on February 6, 1986, Steve Wozniak, the co-founder of Apple Computer, decides to leave to pursue other interests. Reportedly he was unhappy that the company was devoting most of its resources to the Macintosh at the expense of the Apple II. He remained a shareholder on the board and eventually come back as an advisor when Gil Amelio became CEO. He makes sporadic appearances at Apple events but still does not perform in any official capacity at Apple.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 4 years ago, on May 3, 1978, the earliest known case of spam was sent. Today, unsolicited bulk email--better known as spam--accounts for up to 90% of all email messages, but it wasn't until this date in 1978 that the first spam was sent. Gary Thuerk, a Digital Equipment Corporation marketer, composed a message promoting the DECSYSTEM-20 computer. The message promoted two upcoming product presentations of the DECSYSTEM-20 accessing the ARPANET. The reaction to the message was swift and highly negative, including one who claimed that the message shut down his system.

The company was selling online service â€œGamelineâ€ to Atari 2600 users. You would pay $49.95 for the modem and also a one-time $15 setup fee. The company changed to sell Quantum Link for Commodore 64 and 128 consoles. Eventually, they would get into AppleLink and PC Link. Quantum Computer Services eventually (October 1989) changed their name to America Online (AOL).

The magnetic tape media was the first to be on the market, as VHS didnâ€™t come around until 1976. Many believed Betamax was the better of the two in quality. Many TV and professional recording companies used the format almost til the end of their lifetime. Of course, in 1984, the players were under major fire for copyright infringement from Universal. However, it was ruled that although they could record the content, it was not their responsibility if someone used it for illegal activity. Sony finally stopped producing the player and tapes on August, 2002.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 14 years ago, on June 8, 2006 US House of Representatives voted down the Net Neutrality Amendment. The amendment would have formalized Net neutrality policies, a move lobbied for and favored by a number of Silicon Valley tech companies. The vote was split closely down partisan lines, with most dissenting votes coming from the Republican side of the House, while the majority of Democrats were in favor of it. Net neutrality, which calls for an open Internet with no favoritism granted towards certain users, providers, or types of streaming services and data, has been an ongoing debate, especially in the US and Europe.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 42 years ago, on June 11, 1978, Texas Instruments Inc. introduced Speak &amp; Spell, a talking learning aid for ages 7 and up. Its debut marked the first electronic duplication of the human vocal tract on a single chip of silicon. Speak &amp; Spell utilized linear predictive coding to formulate a mathematical model of the human vocal tract and predict a speech sample based on previous input. It transformed digital information processed through a filter into synthetic speech and could store more than 100 seconds of linguistic sounds.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 41 years ago, on June 18, 1979, Microsoft BASIC is introduced for the 8086 16-bit microprocesso, making it compatible with their 8-bit versions and thus helped move forward 16-bit computing. But perhaps more importantly, by developing for 8086, they soon formed a relationship with Seattle Computer Products (SCP), one of the first companies building computers with an 8086 processor. In 1980 SCP was forced to develop an operating system for their computers because a version of the very popular CP/M operating system was delayed for the 8086. It was this 8086 operating system, which SCP called QDOS (for Quick and Dirty Operating System), that Microsoft soon bought the rights for and licensed to IBM for their new PC. And MS thus began their transformation from a simple software development company in the early history of personal computing to one of the most dominant technology companies in history.

X11 is a windowing system for bitmap displays, common on Unix-like operating systems, and provides the basic framework for a GUI environment: drawing and moving windows on the display device and interacting with a mouse and keyboard.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 16 years ago, on June 21, 2004, the first private space flight took place. Financed by Microsoft co-founder Paul Allen, SpaceShipOne becomes the first spacecraft developed by the free market to enter spaceflight. Launched from a mothership named White Knight, SpaceShipOne flew just beyond the atmosphere into the threshold of space then glided back to Earth. SpaceShipOne would later win the $10 million Ansari X Prize for the first non-government organization to launch a reusable manned spacecraft.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 108 years ago, on June 23, 1912, computer pioneer Alan Turing was born. Turing, a British mathematician, logician and cryptanalyst, played key roles in the conception and theoretical underpinnings of electronic computers. As a codebreaker during World War II, Turing led the team that cracked the "unbreakable" Enigma code used by the German high command for battlefield communications. Turing is best-known today for his work on the idea of a "universal computer," one that could run any program. Turing died under mysterious circumstances from cyanide poisoning in 1954, though it was officially declared suicide. He was 41.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 48 years ago, on June 27, 1972, Atari, the iconic video game company, is founded by Nolan Bushnell and Ted Dabney. Their first video game, Pong, was the first commercially successful video game and led to the start of the video game industry. ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 20 years ago, on June 30, 2000, brothers Alan and Vincent Chow announced they successfully placed a silicon microchip beneath human retinas. The Artificial Silicon Retina (ASR) was designed to stimulate damaged retinal cells from within the retina to allow the cells to recreate visual signals that are processed and sent to the brain.The ASR is smaller than the head of a pin and only microns thin. These chips also contain solar cells to help power the chip. In what is called â€œOptobionicsâ€, the chip is inserted behind the retina in the â€œsubretinal spaceâ€. This is a 2-hour procedure and the chip can last up to 8 years after (depending on care).

Originally forecasting sales of just 3,000 to 5,000 per year, the TRS-80 sold over 10,000 units in the first month-and-a-half of sales and 200,000 over the lifetime of the product.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 23 years ago, on August 6, 1997, Steve Jobs announces that Apple and Microsoft have signed a five-year alliance. As part of the deal, MS committed to continuing development of MS Office for Mac over the next five years, Apple would make Internet Explorer the default web browser on the Mac, Apple and MS would collaborate on Java compatibility, and MS invested $150 million in Apple stock. However, the most important part of the arrangement is that both companies would cross-license all existing patents along with any new patents over the next five years, Apple would drop their long-running series of patent-infringement lawsuits against Microsoft, and Microsoft paid an undisclosed amount of money to Apple.

Owned by the corporation GeoEye, Inc., GeoEye-1 is capable of taking high resolution images with detail down to 16 inches. However, the US Government has restricted that resolution for its own use. ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 15 years ago, on September 7, 2005, Apple introduces the iPod Nano, effectively replacing the iPod Mini. The move surprised many in the industry, as the iPod Mini was extremely popular. However, the use of flash storage instead of a hard drive allowed for a much smaller form factor, increased reliability, and better battery life. These improvements proved extremely popular with consumers as one million units were sold in the first 17 days. The pioneering use of flash storage in a consumer electronic device paved the way for its use in many future Apple product designs, such as the iPhone, iPad, and flash storage-based MacBooks.

Star Trek was not an immediate hit and was initially broadcast for only three seasons (a total of 79 episodes). The last episode aired on September 2, 1969.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 31 years ago, on September 18, 1989, the operating system NeXTSTEP was released. It was actually based on the Unix operating system and was very similar in appearance, it also ran off the same C programming language. NeXTSTEP made writing C programming languages far easier than any of the other operating systems even better than the rival Unix even though the creator of Unix created C programming. The current Apple OS X operating system used today is based on NeXTSTEP as it was known as such a good system for its time and was often pointed to as a paragon of computer development even a decade later.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 34 years ago, on September 22, 1986, the US District Court for the Northern District of California rules that computer code is protected under copyright law. The ruling stems from the case NEC Corp. v. Intel Corp, which was basically a battle over who had the right to produce x86 processors. The ruling, while finding that Intel had copyright protection for the code in their processors, also found that reverse-engineering code was also legal and therefore NEC did not violate Intelâ€™s copyright in producing their own x86 processors. This ruling that code could be copyrighted changed the landscape, for better or worse, of software and computer development.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 47 years ago, on September 25, 1973, Micro Computer Machines of Canada introduces what is possibly the earliest commercially manufactured device that can now be considered a personal computer, their MCM/70 microcomputer, at a programmerâ€™s user conference in Toronto. The company worked closely with Intel on the design of their computer and made very early use of the Intel 8008 processor, of which the basic design was used for the future Intel 8086. However, failing to generate venture capital in the Canadian marketplace, the MCM/70 never gained significant market acceptance and by the time the Apple II and other early personal computers were being released, the MCM/70 was relegated to a footnote in history.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ g2 years ago, on October 18, 1958, William Higinbotham and Robert Dvorak, Sr. show off a tennis simulator game they called Tennis for Two. Developed on a Donner Model 30 analog computer using an oscilloscope, it is the first known electronic game to use a graphical display. Higinbotham and Dvorak developed the game to show off to visitors to the Brookhaven National Laboratory where they worked. The game was only shown off twice, during the laboratoryâ€™s annual visitorâ€™s day. While hundreds of visitors lined up to play the game when it was made available, little was known about the game for decades. While somewhat similar in gameplay to the later hit Pong, there is no known direct relationship between the games.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 16 years ago, on October 20, 2004, the first Ubuntu Linux distribution is released. Ubuntu is a free computer operating system based on Debian GNU/Linux. Its name loosely translated from the Zulu means "humanity," or "a person is a person only through other people." Ubuntu is intended to provide an up-to-date, stable operating system for the average user, with a strong focus on usability and ease of installation. Ubuntu has been rated the most popular Linux distribution for the desktop, claiming approximately 30 percent of desktop Linux installations, according to the 2007 Desktop Linux Market survey. Ubuntu is open source and free. It is sponsored by Canonical Ltd., which is owned by South African entrepreneur Mark Shuttleworth.

FACT OF THE DAY: Googleâ€™s name was created accidentally. A spelling error while checking for the domainâ€™s availability was made by Sean Anderson who was going for Googol. A Googol is the digit 1 followed by 100 zeroes and came up in a brainstorming session set to change BackRub, its original commercial name. Larry Page, unsurprisingly, liked Google better.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 12 years ago, on January 9, 2009, through a posting to The Cryptography Mailing List, the pseudonymous Satoshi Nakamoto releases the first version of the Bitcoin software and launches the network of the decentralized peer-to-peer cryptocurrency. Six days earlier, Nakamoto had generated the first block of 50 bitcoins, now known as the Genesis Block. Bitcoin has slowly but steadily gained momentum as its users appreciate the fact that no one entity can control, manipulate, or deactivate the digital currency, along with it being an extremely private form of payment. Bitcoin has the potential to become â€œthe currency of the future,â€ which means it could completely change the way our society functions in regards to money, government, and the economy â€“ which basically means it could change almost everything about the way the world works. Not bad for some open source code.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 43 years ago, on May 3, 1978, the earliest known case of spam was sent. Today, unsolicited bulk email--better known as spam--accounts for up to 90% of all email messages, but it wasn't until this date in 1978 that the first spam was sent. Gary Thuerk, a Digital Equipment Corporation marketer, composed a message promoting the DECSYSTEM-20 computer. The message promoted two upcoming product presentations of the DECSYSTEM-20 accessing the ARPANET. The reaction to the message was swift and highly negative, including one who claimed that the message shut down his system.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 54 years ago, on May 7, 1967, video game developer Ralph Baer plays first two-player game: Fox and Hounds. It was a game where the fox (a red dot) was chased by the hounds (white dots). The controller were two knobs â€“ horizontal and vertical. You would see how long you could avoid the hounds. This was part of a series of more complex video games including shooting games, handball and Ping Pong, ultimately leading to the Magnavox Odyssey TV game system in 1972. Baer passed away on December 8, 2014.

The sub-dominant hand would take care of vowels and lesser-used consonants, while the dominant hand took care of most of the consonants. While recognised as superior to the QWERTY layout, the Dvorak keyboard is not widely used.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 61 years ago, on May 16, 1960, physicist Theodore Maiman creates the first laser light, using a synthetic-ruby crystal device. He was not the first to develop the theories behind lasers nor first to apply for patents, but he was the first to create an operating laser device. The light produced by this device was not a true beam as we think of most lasers today, but rather a pulse. Other researchers would create the first laser beam soon after.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 41 years ago, on May 22, 1980, Namco released an arcade game called Puck-Man. When it was released in the US in October the name was altered to Pac-Man. One of the little known facts about Pac-Man is that it was specifically developed to be popular with women. Most video games of that time had a war or sports theme to them and women were generally not interested in those games. Pac-Mac would be the first game popular with both men and women and was the first video game to become a social phenomenon. Pac-Mac generated over $2.5 billion by the 1990â€™s, becoming one of the highest grossing video games of all time.

Quantum Computer Services eventually (October 1989) changed their name to America Online (AOL).

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 43 years ago, on June 11, 1978, Texas Instruments Inc. introduced Speak &amp; Spell, a talking learning aid for ages 7 and up. Its debut marked the first electronic duplication of the human vocal tract on a single chip of silicon. Speak &amp; Spell utilized linear predictive coding to formulate a mathematical model of the human vocal tract and predict a speech sample based on previous input. It transformed digital information processed through a filter into synthetic speech and could store more than 100 seconds of linguistic sounds.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 42 years ago, on June 18, 1979, Microsoft BASIC is introduced for the 8086 16-bit microprocesso, making it compatible with their 8-bit versions and thus helped move forward 16-bit computing. But perhaps more importantly, by developing for 8086, they soon formed a relationship with Seattle Computer Products (SCP), one of the first companies building computers with an 8086 processor. In 1980 SCP was forced to develop an operating system for their computers because a version of the very popular CP/M operating system was delayed for the 8086. It was this 8086 operating system, which SCP called QDOS (for Quick and Dirty Operating System), that Microsoft soon bought the rights for and licensed to IBM for their new PC. And MS thus began their transformation from a simple software development company in the early history of personal computing to one of the most dominant technology companies in history.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 17 years ago, on June 21, 2004, the first private space flight took place. Financed by Microsoft co-founder Paul Allen, SpaceShipOne becomes the first spacecraft developed by the free market to enter spaceflight. Launched from a mothership named White Knight, SpaceShipOne flew just beyond the atmosphere into the threshold of space then glided back to Earth. SpaceShipOne would later win the $10 million Ansari X Prize for the first non-government organization to launch a reusable manned spacecraft.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 109 years ago, on June 23, 1912, computer pioneer Alan Turing was born. Turing, a British mathematician, logician and cryptanalyst, played key roles in the conception and theoretical underpinnings of electronic computers. As a codebreaker during World War II, Turing led the team that cracked the "unbreakable" Enigma code used by the German high command for battlefield communications. Turing is best-known today for his work on the idea of a "universal computer," one that could run any program. Turing died under mysterious circumstances from cyanide poisoning in 1954, though it was officially declared suicide. He was 41.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 21 years ago, on June 30, 2000, brothers Alan and Vincent Chow announced they successfully placed a silicon microchip beneath human retinas. The Artificial Silicon Retina (ASR) was designed to stimulate damaged retinal cells from within the retina to allow the cells to recreate visual signals that are processed and sent to the brain.The ASR is smaller than the head of a pin and only microns thin. These chips also contain solar cells to help power the chip. In what is called â€œOptobionicsâ€, the chip is inserted behind the retina in the â€œsubretinal spaceâ€. This is a 2-hour procedure and the chip can last up to 8 years after (depending on care).

She worked on early computers such as the Harvard Mark I. ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 44 years ago, on August 3, 1977, Radio Shack introduces their first computer, the TRS-80. With the support of 3500 Radio Shack stores plus a relatively low cost, the TRS-80 helped drive the acceptance of the personal computer in the home. Originally forecasting sales of just 3,000 to 5,000 per year, the TRS-80 sold over 10,000 units in the first month-and-a-half of sales and 200,000 over the lifetime of the product.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 24 years ago, on August 6, 1997, Steve Jobs announces that Apple and Microsoft have signed a five-year alliance. As part of the deal, MS committed to continuing development of MS Office for Mac over the next five years, Apple would make Internet Explorer the default web browser on the Mac, Apple and MS would collaborate on Java compatibility, and MS invested $150 million in Apple stock. However, the most important part of the arrangement is that both companies would cross-license all existing patents along with any new patents over the next five years, Apple would drop their long-running series of patent-infringement lawsuits against Microsoft, and Microsoft paid an undisclosed amount of money to Apple.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 13 years ago, on September 6, 2008, after 5 months of delays, the high resolution earth observation satellite, GeoEye-1, is launched from Vandenburg Air Force Base. Owned by the corporation GeoEye, Inc., GeoEye-1 is capable of taking high resolution images with detail down to 16 inches. However, the US Government has restricted that resolution for its own use. Commercial usage is limited to resolutions with detail down to 20 inches. As the exclusive licensee of the images for online mapping purposes, Google had its logo on the Delta II rocket that was used to launch GeoEye-1.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 16 years ago, on September 7, 2005, Apple introduces the iPod Nano, effectively replacing the iPod Mini. The move surprised many in the industry, as the iPod Mini was extremely popular. However, the use of flash storage instead of a hard drive allowed for a much smaller form factor, increased reliability, and better battery life. These improvements proved extremely popular with consumers as one million units were sold in the first 17 days. The pioneering use of flash storage in a consumer electronic device paved the way for its use in many future Apple product designs, such as the iPhone, iPad, and flash storage-based MacBooks.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 55 years ago, on September 8, 1966, the first episode of Star Trek airs. Star Trek, the science fiction television series, was created by Gene Roddenberry. Kirk (played by William Shatner), his First Officer Mr. Spock (Leonard Nimoy), and his Chief Medical Officer Leonard McCoy (DeForest Kelley). Star Trek was not an immediate hit and was initially broadcast for only three seasons (a total of 79 episodes). Many of the technologies shown in the series, including the â€œTricorderâ€ and personal communicator, influenced a generation of technologists working in portable communications and computing. The last episode aired on September 2, 1969.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 74 years ago, on September 9, 1947, the first instance of an actual computer bug was found. At 3:45pm, Grace Murray Hopper records 'the first computer bug' in the Harvard Mark II computer's log book. The problem was traced to a moth stuck between relay contacts in the computer, which Hopper duly taped into the Mark II's log book with the explanation: â€œFirst actual case of bug being found.â€

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 32 years ago, on September 18, 1989, the operating system NeXTSTEP was released. It was actually based on the Unix operating system and was very similar in appearance, it also ran off the same C programming language. NeXTSTEP made writing C programming languages far easier than any of the other operating systems even better than the rival Unix even though the creator of Unix created C programming. The current Apple OS X operating system used today is based on NeXTSTEP as it was known as such a good system for its time and was often pointed to as a paragon of computer development even a decade later.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 35 years ago, on September 22, 1986, the US District Court for the Northern District of California rules that computer code is protected under copyright law. The ruling stems from the case NEC Corp. v. Intel Corp, which was basically a battle over who had the right to produce x86 processors. The ruling, while finding that Intel had copyright protection for the code in their processors, also found that reverse-engineering code was also legal and therefore NEC did not violate Intelâ€™s copyright in producing their own x86 processors. This ruling that code could be copyrighted changed the landscape, for better or worse, of software and computer development.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 42 years ago, on September 24, 1979, CompuServe launches the first consumer-oriented online information service, which they called MicroNET. This marked the first time a consumer had access to services such as e-mail. By the mid-1980â€™s CompuServe was the largest consumer information service in the world and half their revenue came from CIS. In 1989 CompuServe connected its proprietary e-mail system to the Internet e-mail system, making it one of the first commercial Internet services. However, CompuServe did not compete well with America On-Line or independent Internet Service Providers in the 1990â€™s and lost its dominant market position.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 48 years ago, on September 25, 1973, Micro Computer Machines of Canada introduces what is possibly the earliest commercially manufactured device that can now be considered a personal computer, their MCM/70 microcomputer, at a programmerâ€™s user conference in Toronto. The company worked closely with Intel on the design of their computer and made very early use of the Intel 8008 processor, of which the basic design was used for the future Intel 8086. However, failing to generate venture capital in the Canadian marketplace, the MCM/70 never gained significant market acceptance and by the time the Apple II and other early personal computers were being released, the MCM/70 was relegated to a footnote in history.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 38 years ago, on September 29, 1983, Microsoft releases their first software application, Microsoft Word 1.0. For use with MS-DOS compatible systems, Word was the first word processing software to make extensive use of a computer mouse. Not coincidentally, Microsoft had released a computer mouse for IBM-compatible PCs earlier in the year. A demo version was also included for free with a copy of PC World magazine, marking the first time a floppy disk was included with a magazine.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 215 years ago, on October 7th, 1806 Carbon paper was patented in London by inventor Ralph Wedgewood. It was first invented by Pellegrino Turri in 1801. Mostly used for making one or more copies simultaneously with the creation of an original document when using a typewriter or a ballpoint pen, its legacy is in the header of our emails. IMDb attracts over 160 million visitors the site each month.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 63 years ago, on October 18, 1958, William Higinbotham and Robert Dvorak, Sr. show off a tennis simulator game they called Tennis for Two. Developed on a Donner Model 30 analog computer using an oscilloscope, it is the first known electronic game to use a graphical display. Higinbotham and Dvorak developed the game to show off to visitors to the Brookhaven National Laboratory where they worked. The game was only shown off twice, during the laboratoryâ€™s annual visitorâ€™s day. While hundreds of visitors lined up to play the game when it was made available, little was known about the game for decades. While somewhat similar in gameplay to the later hit Pong, there is no known direct relationship between the games.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 17 years ago, on October 20, 2004, the first Ubuntu Linux distribution is released. Ubuntu is a free computer operating system based on Debian GNU/Linux. Its name loosely translated from the Zulu means "humanity," or "a person is a person only through other people." Ubuntu is intended to provide an up-to-date, stable operating system for the average user, with a strong focus on usability and ease of installation. Ubuntu has been rated the most popular Linux distribution for the desktop, claiming approximately 30 percent of desktop Linux installations, according to the 2007 Desktop Linux Market survey. Ubuntu is open source and free. It is sponsored by Canonical Ltd., which is owned by South African entrepreneur Mark Shuttleworth.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 41 years ago, on October 27, 1980, the first major network Crash, the Four-Hour Collapse of the ARPANET, occurred. The ARPANET, predecessor of the modern Internet, was set up by the Department of Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA). Initially it had linked four sites in California and Utah, and later was expanded to cover research centers across the country. The network failure resulted from a redundant single-error detecting code that was used for transmission but not storage, and a garbage-collection algorithm for removing old messages that was not resistant to the simultaneous existence of one message with several different time stamps. The combination of the events took the network down for four hours.

UCLA student Charley Kline attempts to transmit the text â€œloginâ€ to a computer at the Stanford Research Institute over the first link on the ARPANET, which was the precursor to the modern Internet. After the letters â€œlâ€ and â€œoâ€ are sent the system crashed, making the first message ever sent on the Internet â€œloâ€. About an hour later, after recovering from the crash, the full text of â€œloginâ€ is successfully sent.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 16 years ago, on November 1, 2005, a software glitch halts Tokyo stock exchange. A software error related to a system upgrade halted stock and bond trading on the Tokyo Stock Exchange. ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 33 years ago, on November 2, 1988, Robert Morris of Cornell University launches a self-replicating worm as part of a research project designed to determine the size of the early Internet. It was intended to count the number of computers that initiated connections when the worm was loaded onto them. However, due to a programming error, the â€œMorris Wormâ€ began repeatedly infecting machines, clogging network traffic and causing machines to crash. Eventually the worm spread to 6,000 machines, which was roughly 10 percent of the Internet at the time, causing significant downtime for government and university systems for two days. Morris was dismissed from Cornell, sentenced to three years probation and a $10,000 fine.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 15 years ago, on November 5, 2006, Internet boasts 100 million sites. According to Internet services company Netcraft Ltd., on this day over 100 million Web sites existed on the Internet. The first Netcraft survey in August 1995 found 18,957 hosts.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 84 years ago, on November 12, 1937, Alan Turing defines the Universal Machine. Alan Turingâ€™s paper entitled On Computable Numbers with an Application to the Entscheidungs-problem appeared on November 12, 1937, somewhat contemporaneously with Konrad Zuseâ€™s work on the first of the Z machines in Germany, John Vincent Atanasoff â€˜s work on the ABC, George Stibitzâ€™s work on the Bell Telephony relay machine, and Howard Aikenâ€™s on the Automatic Sequence Controlled Calculator. Later renamed the Turing Machine, this abstract engine provided the fundamental concepts of computers that the other inventors would realize independently. So Turing provided the abstraction that would form the basic theory of computability for several decades, while others provided the pragmatic means of computation.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 24 years ago, on November 14, 1997, one week after reports surfaced identifying a flaw in certain Pentium processors, Intel releases a software workaround for operating systems to avoid the commonly named â€œF0 bugâ€œ. A very specific invalid operation passed to the affected processors would cause the processor to lock up, causing the computer and any software running on it to freeze. Identified by Intel as the â€œInvalid Operand with Locked Compare Exchange 8Byte (CMPXCHG8B) Instruction Erratumâ€ (seriously?), the flaw, while potentially a serious problem, was practically little more than a PR headache as the invalid operation that triggered the processor to lock up was never encountered in real-world operations. Additionally, the F0 bug only affected the older Pentium processors, not the Pentium II and Pentium Pro processors Intel was currently shipping at the time. However, the workaround was necessary as malicious software could have exploited the flaw and caused serious problems for PCs and servers using the affected processors.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 29 years ago, on November 23, 1992, Business Week predicts Computer Industry "on the skids". With IBM projected to lose $5 billion in 1992, Business Week describes the computer business as "an industry on the skids." The magazine cited layoffs at most established computer companies, such as IBM, as well as newer firms like Sun Microsystems, Inc., as evidence that the industry was saturated. A solution, the article concluded, would be for each business to find its proper niche.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 19 years ago, on November 25, 2002, digital media software company Roxio purchases the assets of the former Napster, including name, logo and other intellectual property. Napster was the peer-to-peer file sharing service that changed the music industry forever. The RIAA sued Napster causing a judgement against the file-sharing service requiring them to monitor its network for copyright infringing material and restrict access when made aware of such incidents. Napster could not comply with this court order and shut down its service before declaring bankruptcy in 2002. Roxio was the first company to attempt to use the Napster brand for a music service, renaming Pressplay as Napster 2.0. In September 2008, Best Buy purchased the Napster service for $121 million before merging it with the Rhapsody service in December 2011.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 206 years ago, on December 10 1815, Augusta Ada King, Lady Lovelace, regarded as the first computer programmer, is born. Her father was Lord Byron, the famous poet. Ada worked with Charles Babbage writing extensive comments on his Difference Engine and Analytical Engine, and programming for the last one. A century later, in the 1970s, the computer language ADA was developed and named after Ada, Lady Lovelace. Based on the language PASCAL, ADA is a general-purpose language designed to be readable and easily maintained.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 75 years ago, on December 11 1946, a patent is issued for Sir Frederick Williams' device for random-access memory. The Williams tube was a modified cathode-ray tube that painted dots and dashes of phosphorescent electrical charge on a screen representing binary ones and zeros. It became the primary memory for vacuum tube machines such as the IBM 701. Williams developed his device at Manchester University and it served as the precursor of more advanced memories for commercial computers.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 30 years ago, on December 13 1991, The Stanford Linear Accelerator Center (SLAC) put up the first Website outside Europe. It let physicists browse the full text of pre-publication scientific papers on SLAC's SPIRES database directly over the Web. This was a radical improvement over the old system, which involved submitting requests and waiting for fax or email versions to be sent back. As a vital service for the international physics community, the SLAC site became an important early step in helping the World Wide Web live up to its ambitious name.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 69 years ago, on December 14 1952, The US Navy issues a formal Letter of Intent to MIT for development of the Airplane Stability and Control Analyzer (ASCA) program, the beginning of the project Whirlwind. Constructed under the leadership of Jay W. Forrester, the Whirlwind was the first high-speed electronic digital computer that was able to operate in real time with electronic reliability. By December 1954, the computer comprised 12,500 vacuum tubes and 23,800 crystal diodes, occupying a two-story building. It operated until 1959.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 13 years ago, on January 9, 2009, through a posting to The Cryptography Mailing List, the pseudonymous Satoshi Nakamoto releases the first version of the Bitcoin software and launches the network of the decentralized peer-to-peer cryptocurrency. Six days earlier, Nakamoto had generated the first block of 50 bitcoins, now known as the Genesis Block. Bitcoin has slowly but steadily gained momentum as its users appreciate the fact that no one entity can control, manipulate, or deactivate the digital currency, along with it being an extremely private form of payment. Bitcoin has the potential to become â€œthe currency of the future,â€ which means it could completely change the way our society functions in regards to money, government, and the economy â€“ which basically means it could change almost everything about the way the world works. Not bad for some open source code.

TODAY, April 6, 2019, a GPS Week Rollover is taking place. It happens because the current week number is encoded using a 10-bit field, and this allows for a week range from zero to 1023. The current period began back on 22 August 1999, and on 6 April 2019 the week number rolls over back to zero. While most modern GPS receivers shouldn't be affected by this, testing showed that there is a possibility that some will interpret this rollover as the date shifting back to January 6, 1980, or possibly some other incorrect date.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 44 years ago, on May 3, 1978, the earliest known case of spam was sent. Today, unsolicited bulk email--better known as spam--accounts for up to 90% of all email messages, but it wasn't until this date in 1978 that the first spam was sent. Gary Thuerk, a Digital Equipment Corporation marketer, composed a message promoting the DECSYSTEM-20 computer. The message promoted two upcoming product presentations of the DECSYSTEM-20 accessing the ARPANET. The reaction to the message was swift and highly negative, including one who claimed that the message shut down his system.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 55 years ago, on May 7, 1967, video game developer Ralph Baer plays first two-player game: Fox and Hounds. It was a game where the fox (a red dot) was chased by the hounds (white dots). The controller were two knobs â€“ horizontal and vertical. You would see how long you could avoid the hounds. This was part of a series of more complex video games including shooting games, handball and Ping Pong, ultimately leading to the Magnavox Odyssey TV game system in 1972. Baer passed away on December 8, 2014.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 86 years ago, on May 12, 1936, University of Washington education professor August Dvorak received a patent for his new more efficient keyboard layout. Key letters were together so you would â€œrollâ€ words. T was next to H, N was next to S. The sub-dominant hand would take care of vowels and lesser-used consonants, while the dominant hand took care of most of the consonants. While recognised as superior to the QWERTY layout, the Dvorak keyboard is not widely used.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 62 years ago, on May 16, 1960, physicist Theodore Maiman creates the first laser light, using a synthetic-ruby crystal device. He was not the first to develop the theories behind lasers nor first to apply for patents, but he was the first to create an operating laser device. The light produced by this device was not a true beam as we think of most lasers today, but rather a pulse. Other researchers would create the first laser beam soon after.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 40 years ago, on May 22, 1980, Namco released an arcade game called Puck-Man. When it was released in the US in October the name was altered to Pac-Man. One of the little known facts about Pac-Man is that it was specifically developed to be popular with women. Most video games of that time had a war or sports theme to them and women were generally not interested in those games. Pac-Mac would be the first game popular with both men and women and was the first video game to become a social phenomenon. Pac-Mac generated over $2.5 billion by the 1990â€™s, becoming one of the highest grossing video games of all time.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 37 years ago, on May 24, 1985, Quantum Computer Services (AOL) was founded. Technically, it was a reorganization of Control Video Corporation, a company that started in 1983. The company was selling online service â€œGamelineâ€ to Atari 2600 users. You would pay $49.95 for the modem and also a one-time $15 setup fee. The company changed to sell Quantum Link for Commodore 64 and 128 consoles. Eventually, they would get into AppleLink and PC Link. Quantum Computer Services eventually (October 1989) changed their name to America Online (AOL).

The magnetic tape media was the first to be on the market, as VHS didnâ€™t come around until 1976. Many believed Betamax was the better of the two in quality. However, it was ruled that although they could record the content, it was not their responsibility if someone used it for illegal activity. Sony finally stopped producing the player and tapes on August, 2002.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 16 years ago, on June 8, 2006 US House of Representatives voted down the Net Neutrality Amendment. The amendment would have formalized Net neutrality policies, a move lobbied for and favored by a number of Silicon Valley tech companies. The vote was split closely down partisan lines, with most dissenting votes coming from the Republican side of the House, while the majority of Democrats were in favor of it. Net neutrality, which calls for an open Internet with no favoritism granted towards certain users, providers, or types of streaming services and data, has been an ongoing debate, especially in the US and Europe.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 44 years ago, on June 11, 1978, Texas Instruments Inc. introduced Speak &amp; Spell, a talking learning aid for ages 7 and up. Its debut marked the first electronic duplication of the human vocal tract on a single chip of silicon. Speak &amp; Spell utilized linear predictive coding to formulate a mathematical model of the human vocal tract and predict a speech sample based on previous input. It transformed digital information processed through a filter into synthetic speech and could store more than 100 seconds of linguistic sounds.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 18 years ago, on June 21, 2004, the first private space flight took place. Financed by Microsoft co-founder Paul Allen, SpaceShipOne becomes the first spacecraft developed by the free market to enter spaceflight. Launched from a mothership named White Knight, SpaceShipOne flew just beyond the atmosphere into the threshold of space then glided back to Earth. SpaceShipOne would later win the $10 million Ansari X Prize for the first non-government organization to launch a reusable manned spacecraft.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 110 years ago, on June 23, 1912, computer pioneer Alan Turing was born. Turing, a British mathematician, logician and cryptanalyst, played key roles in the conception and theoretical underpinnings of electronic computers. As a codebreaker during World War II, Turing led the team that cracked the "unbreakable" Enigma code used by the German high command for battlefield communications. Turing is best-known today for his work on the idea of a "universal computer," one that could run any program. Turing died under mysterious circumstances from cyanide poisoning in 1954, though it was officially declared suicide. He was 41.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 22 years ago, on June 30, 2000, brothers Alan and Vincent Chow announced they successfully placed a silicon microchip beneath human retinas. The Artificial Silicon Retina (ASR) was designed to stimulate damaged retinal cells from within the retina to allow the cells to recreate visual signals that are processed and sent to the brain.The ASR is smaller than the head of a pin and only microns thin. These chips also contain solar cells to help power the chip. In what is called â€œOptobionicsâ€, the chip is inserted behind the retina in the â€œsubretinal spaceâ€. This is a 2-hour procedure and the chip can last up to 8 years after (depending on care).

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 41 years ago, on July 28, 1981, IBM introduced its System/23 Datamaster desktop computer, only two weeks before they introduce their IBM PC. Geared towards small business for use as a word and data processor, the computer was designed to be set up by end-users without the need of a computer specialist. While now a footnote in history, the importance of the Datamaster is that many of the team members that developed it were re-assigned to the secret IBM PC project and much of the knowledge they acquired went into developing the IBM PC as quickly as possible.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 43 years ago, on July 30, 1979, Apple begins work on the Lisa, which would become the worldâ€™s first commercial computer with a graphical user interface. Originally intended to sell for $2,000 and ship in 1981, the Lisa is delayed until 1983 and sells for $10,000. Utilizing technology that was ahead of its time, the high cost, relative lack of software, and some hardware reliability issues ultimately sink the success of the Lisa. However, much of the technology introduced by the Lisa influenced the development of the Macintosh as well as other future computer and operating system designs.

Throughout her career, she made many important contributions to the use of computers in solving applied mathematical problems and was known for her strong administrative skills and influence. In 1970, she became the first female president of the American Association for the Advancement of Science (AAAS).

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 45 years ago, on August 3, 1977, Radio Shack introduces their first computer, the TRS-80. With the support of 3500 Radio Shack stores plus a relatively low cost, the TRS-80 helped drive the acceptance of the personal computer in the home. Originally forecasting sales of just 3,000 to 5,000 per year, the TRS-80 sold over 10,000 units in the first month-and-a-half of sales and 200,000 over the lifetime of the product.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 25 years ago, on August 6, 1997, Steve Jobs announces that Apple and Microsoft have signed a five-year alliance. As part of the deal, MS committed to continuing development of MS Office for Mac over the next five years, Apple would make Internet Explorer the default web browser on the Mac, Apple and MS would collaborate on Java compatibility, and MS invested $150 million in Apple stock. However, the most important part of the arrangement is that both companies would cross-license all existing patents along with any new patents over the next five years, Apple would drop their long-running series of patent-infringement lawsuits against Microsoft, and Microsoft paid an undisclosed amount of money to Apple.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 14 years ago, on September 6, 2008, after 5 months of delays, the high resolution earth observation satellite, GeoEye-1, is launched from Vandenburg Air Force Base. Owned by the corporation GeoEye, Inc., GeoEye-1 is capable of taking high resolution images with detail down to 16 inches. However, the US Government has restricted that resolution for its own use. Commercial usage is limited to resolutions with detail down to 20 inches. As the exclusive licensee of the images for online mapping purposes, Google had its logo on the Delta II rocket that was used to launch GeoEye-1.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 17 years ago, on September 7, 2005, Apple introduces the iPod Nano, effectively replacing the iPod Mini. The move surprised many in the industry, as the iPod Mini was extremely popular. However, the use of flash storage instead of a hard drive allowed for a much smaller form factor, increased reliability, and better battery life. These improvements proved extremely popular with consumers as one million units were sold in the first 17 days. The pioneering use of flash storage in a consumer electronic device paved the way for its use in many future Apple product designs, such as the iPhone, iPad, and flash storage-based MacBooks.

Star Trek was not an immediate hit and was initially broadcast for only three seasons (a total of 79 episodes). Many of the technologies shown in the series, including the â€œTricorderâ€ and personal communicator, influenced a generation of technologists working in portable communications and computing. The last episode aired on September 2, 1969.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 33 years ago, on September 18, 1989, the operating system NeXTSTEP was released. NeXTSTEP made writing C programming languages far easier than any of the other operating systems even better than the rival Unix even though the creator of Unix created C programming. The current Apple OS X operating system used today is based on NeXTSTEP as it was known as such a good system for its time and was often pointed to as a paragon of computer development even a decade later.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 36 years ago, on September 22, 1986, the US District Court for the Northern District of California rules that computer code is protected under copyright law. The ruling stems from the case NEC Corp. v. Intel Corp, which was basically a battle over who had the right to produce x86 processors. The ruling, while finding that Intel had copyright protection for the code in their processors, also found that reverse-engineering code was also legal and therefore NEC did not violate Intelâ€™s copyright in producing their own x86 processors. This ruling that code could be copyrighted changed the landscape, for better or worse, of software and computer development.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 49 years ago, on September 25, 1973, Micro Computer Machines of Canada introduces what is possibly the earliest commercially manufactured device that can now be considered a personal computer, their MCM/70 microcomputer, at a programmerâ€™s user conference in Toronto. The company worked closely with Intel on the design of their computer and made very early use of the Intel 8008 processor, of which the basic design was used for the future Intel 8086. However, failing to generate venture capital in the Canadian marketplace, the MCM/70 never gained significant market acceptance and by the time the Apple II and other early personal computers were being released, the MCM/70 was relegated to a footnote in history.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 64 years ago, on October 18, 1958, William Higinbotham and Robert Dvorak, Sr. show off a tennis simulator game they called Tennis for Two. Developed on a Donner Model 30 analog computer using an oscilloscope, it is the first known electronic game to use a graphical display. Higinbotham and Dvorak developed the game to show off to visitors to the Brookhaven National Laboratory where they worked. The game was only shown off twice, during the laboratoryâ€™s annual visitorâ€™s day. While hundreds of visitors lined up to play the game when it was made available, little was known about the game for decades. While somewhat similar in gameplay to the later hit Pong, there is no known direct relationship between the games.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 18 years ago, on October 20, 2004, the first Ubuntu Linux distribution is released. Ubuntu is a free computer operating system based on Debian GNU/Linux. Its name loosely translated from the Zulu means "humanity," or "a person is a person only through other people." Ubuntu is intended to provide an up-to-date, stable operating system for the average user, with a strong focus on usability and ease of installation. Ubuntu has been rated the most popular Linux distribution for the desktop, claiming approximately 30 percent of desktop Linux installations, according to the 2007 Desktop Linux Market survey. Ubuntu is open source and free. It is sponsored by Canonical Ltd., which is owned by South African entrepreneur Mark Shuttleworth.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 143 years ago, on October 21, 1879, Thomas Edison perfects the first commercially practical incandescent light bulb. Using a filament of carbonized cotton thread, his first attempt at this design results in a bulb that lasts about 13.5 hours before burning out. He later extends the life of the bulb to 40 hours. Edisonâ€™s successful design came only after he had tested over 6,000 different vegetable fibers during a span of over 18 months running 1,200 experiments and spending $40,000.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 84 years ago, on October 22, 1938, photocopying was invented.<br>In a makeshift lab on the second floor of a rental house, Chester Carlson and his assistant Otto Kornei successfully invented the process that would lead to the photocopier. Carlson had written â€œ10.-22.-38 ASTORIAâ€ on a piece of paper and these became the historic words that were the first photocopied. Ironically, Kornei had so little faith in the invention that within a year he quit working for Carlson and willingly gave up any claims he had on the process. However, Carlson would later gift Kornei 100 shares of the Xerox corporation that would eventually be worth $1 million.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 42 years ago, on October 27, 1980, the first major network Crash, the Four-Hour Collapse of the ARPANET, occurred. The ARPANET, predecessor of the modern Internet, was set up by the Department of Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA). Initially it had linked four sites in California and Utah, and later was expanded to cover research centers across the country. The network failure resulted from a redundant single-error detecting code that was used for transmission but not storage, and a garbage-collection algorithm for removing old messages that was not resistant to the simultaneous existence of one message with several different time stamps. The combination of the events took the network down for four hours.

UCLA student Charley Kline attempts to transmit the text â€œloginâ€ to a computer at the Stanford Research Institute over the first link on the ARPANET, which was the precursor to the modern Internet. After the letters â€œlâ€ and â€œoâ€ are sent the system crashed, making the first message ever sent on the Internet â€œloâ€. ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 17 years ago, on November 1, 2005, a software glitch halts Tokyo stock exchange. A software error related to a system upgrade halted stock and bond trading on the Tokyo Stock Exchange. ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 34 years ago, on November 2, 1988, Robert Morris of Cornell University launches a self-replicating worm as part of a research project designed to determine the size of the early Internet. It was intended to count the number of computers that initiated connections when the worm was loaded onto them. However, due to a programming error, the â€œMorris Wormâ€ began repeatedly infecting machines, clogging network traffic and causing machines to crash. Eventually the worm spread to 6,000 machines, which was roughly 10 percent of the Internet at the time, causing significant downtime for government and university systems for two days. Morris was dismissed from Cornell, sentenced to three years probation and a $10,000 fine.

Laika, a Siberian Husky dog, unfortunately only survived a few hours into the flight and died from stress and overheating. ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 70 years ago, on November 4, 1952, CBS News uses UNIVAC computer to predict election, a race between Dwight D. Eisenhower and Adlai Stevenson. The computer's analysis of early returns showed an easy victory for Eisenhower, but newscasters Walter Cronkite and Charles Collingwood were wary of the machine's accuracy, as opinion polls predicted a landslide victory for Stevenson. They postponed announcing the UNIVAC prediction until it became clear that Eisenhower would, indeed, win.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 16 years ago, on November 5, 2006, Internet boasts 100 million sites. According to Internet services company Netcraft Ltd., on this day over 100 million Web sites existed on the Internet. The milestone capped an extraordinary year in which the Internet added 27.4 million sites, easily topping the previous full-year growth record of 17 million from 2005. The Internet doubled in number of sites since May 2004, when the survey hit 50 million. Blogs and small business Web sites drove the explosive growth in 2006, with huge increases in free blogging services at Google and Microsoft. The first Netcraft survey in August 1995 found 18,957 hosts.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 25 years ago, on November 14, 1997, one week after reports surfaced identifying a flaw in certain Pentium processors, Intel releases a software workaround for operating systems to avoid the commonly named â€œF0 bugâ€œ. A very specific invalid operation passed to the affected processors would cause the processor to lock up, causing the computer and any software running on it to freeze. Identified by Intel as the â€œInvalid Operand with Locked Compare Exchange 8Byte (CMPXCHG8B) Instruction Erratumâ€ (seriously?), the flaw, while potentially a serious problem, was practically little more than a PR headache as the invalid operation that triggered the processor to lock up was never encountered in real-world operations. Additionally, the F0 bug only affected the older Pentium processors, not the Pentium II and Pentium Pro processors Intel was currently shipping at the time. However, the workaround was necessary as malicious software could have exploited the flaw and caused serious problems for PCs and servers using the affected processors.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 52 years ago, on November 17, 1970, the computer mouse was patented. Douglas Engelbart receives US patent 3,541,541 for his â€œX-Y Position Indicator For A Display Systemâ€, more commonly known as the computer mouse. Engelbart called his device a â€œmouseâ€ because the cord looked like a tail. The mouse was first prototyped in 1964, but wasnâ€™t demoed until 1968, and was not included with a commercial computer until the Xerox 8010 Star Information System in 1981. Apple first brought the mouse to a personal computer with the Lisa in 1983. However the mouse did not become ubiquitous until after 1984, when Appleâ€™s Macintosh popularized the device.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 20 years ago, on November 25, 2002, digital media software company Roxio purchases the assets of the former Napster, including name, logo and other intellectual property. Napster was the peer-to-peer file sharing service that changed the music industry forever. The RIAA sued Napster causing a judgement against the file-sharing service requiring them to monitor its network for copyright infringing material and restrict access when made aware of such incidents. Napster could not comply with this court order and shut down its service before declaring bankruptcy in 2002. Roxio was the first company to attempt to use the Napster brand for a music service, renaming Pressplay as Napster 2.0. In September 2008, Best Buy purchased the Napster service for $121 million before merging it with the Rhapsody service in December 2011.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 74 years ago, on November 28, 1948. Polaroid instant camera goes on Sale. Producing sepia toned photographs in about one minute, the Model 95 became a hit almost as quickly. Polaroid believed that 57 units would be enough last through Christmas. All 57 units and all the film available were sold on the first day. It was simple to use, portable, and the instant gratification that came from the self-developing film made the camera very popular. True black-and-white instant film was released in 1950, but Polaroid didnâ€™t create color film until 1963.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 207 years ago, on December 10 1815, Augusta Ada King, Lady Lovelace, regarded as the first computer programmer, is born. Her father was Lord Byron, the famous poet. Ada worked with Charles Babbage writing extensive comments on his Difference Engine and Analytical Engine, and programming for the last one. A century later, in the 1970s, the computer language ADA was developed and named after Ada, Lady Lovelace. Based on the language PASCAL, ADA is a general-purpose language designed to be readable and easily maintained.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 76 years ago, on December 11 1946, a patent is issued for Sir Frederick Williams' device for random-access memory. The Williams tube was a modified cathode-ray tube that painted dots and dashes of phosphorescent electrical charge on a screen representing binary ones and zeros. It became the primary memory for vacuum tube machines such as the IBM 701. Williams developed his device at Manchester University and it served as the precursor of more advanced memories for commercial computers.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 31 years ago, on December 13 1991, The Stanford Linear Accelerator Center (SLAC) put up the first Website outside Europe. It let physicists browse the full text of pre-publication scientific papers on SLAC's SPIRES database directly over the Web. This was a radical improvement over the old system, which involved submitting requests and waiting for fax or email versions to be sent back. As a vital service for the international physics community, the SLAC site became an important early step in helping the World Wide Web live up to its ambitious name.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 70 years ago, on December 14 1952, The US Navy issues a formal Letter of Intent to MIT for development of the Airplane Stability and Control Analyzer (ASCA) program, the beginning of the project Whirlwind. Constructed under the leadership of Jay W. Forrester, the Whirlwind was the first high-speed electronic digital computer that was able to operate in real time with electronic reliability. By December 1954, the computer comprised 12,500 vacuum tubes and 23,800 crystal diodes, occupying a two-story building. It operated until 1959.

ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 14 years ago, on January 9, 2009, through a posting to The Cryptography Mailing List, the pseudonymous Satoshi Nakamoto releases the first version of the Bitcoin software and launches the network of the decentralized peer-to-peer cryptocurrency. Six days earlier, Nakamoto had generated the first block of 50 bitcoins, now known as the Genesis Block. Bitcoin has slowly but steadily gained momentum as its users appreciate the fact that no one entity can control, manipulate, or deactivate the digital currency, along with it being an extremely private form of payment. Bitcoin has the potential to become â€œthe currency of the future,â€ which means it could completely change the way our society functions in regards to money, government, and the economy â€“ which basically means it could change almost everything about the way the world works. Not bad for some open source code.

ON THIS DAY... 37 years ago, on February 6, 1986, Steve Wozniak, the co-founder of Apple Computer, decides to leave to pursue other interests. Reportedly he was unhappy that the company was devoting most of its resources to the Macintosh at the expense of the Apple II. He remained a shareholder on the board and eventually come back as an advisor when Gil Amelio became CEO. He makes sporadic appearances at Apple events but still does not perform in any official capacity at Apple.

<i class="emoji" style="background-image:url('//telegram.org/img/emoji/40/F09F9396.png')"><b>ğŸ“–</b></i> ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 44 years ago, on June 18, 1979, Microsoft BASIC is introduced for the 8086 16-bit microprocesso, making it compatible with their 8-bit versions and thus helped move forward 16-bit computing. But perhaps more importantly, by developing for 8086, they soon formed a relationship with Seattle Computer Products (SCP), one of the first companies building computers with an 8086 processor. In 1980 SCP was forced to develop an operating system for their computers because a version of the very popular CP/M operating system was delayed for the 8086. It was this 8086 operating system, which SCP called QDOS (for Quick and Dirty Operating System), that Microsoft soon bought the rights for and licensed to IBM for their new PC. And MS thus began their transformation from a simple software development company in the early history of personal computing to one of the most dominant technology companies in history.

The ruling stems from the case NEC Corp. v. Intel Corp, which was basically a battle over who had the right to produce x86 processors. The ruling, while finding that Intel had copyright protection for the code in their processors, also found that reverse-engineering code was also legal and therefore NEC did not violate Intelâ€™s copyright in producing their own x86 processors. This ruling that code could be copyrighted changed the landscape, for better or worse, of software and computer development.

<i class="emoji" style="background-image:url('//telegram.org/img/emoji/40/F09F9396.png')"><b>ğŸ“–</b></i> ON THIS DAYâ€¦ 43 years ago, on October 27, 1980, the first major network Crash, the Four-Hour Collapse of the ARPANET, occurred. The ARPANET, predecessor of the modern Internet, was set up by the Department of Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA). Initially it had linked four sites in California and Utah, and later was expanded to cover research centers across the country. The network failure resulted from a redundant single-error detecting code that was used for transmission but not storage, and a garbage-collection algorithm for removing old messages that was not resistant to the simultaneous existence of one message with several different time stamps. The combination of the events took the network down for four hours.

It was intended to count the number of computers that initiated connections when the worm was loaded onto them. However, due to a programming error, the â€œMorris Wormâ€ began repeatedly infecting machines, clogging network traffic and causing machines to crash. Eventually the worm spread to 6,000 machines, which was roughly 10 percent of the Internet at the time, causing significant downtime for government and university systems for two days. Morris was dismissed from Cornell, sentenced to three years probation and a $10,000 fine.

A very specific invalid operation passed to the affected processors would cause the processor to lock up, causing the computer and any software running on it to freeze. Identified by Intel as the â€œInvalid Operand with Locked Compare Exchange 8Byte (CMPXCHG8B) Instruction Erratumâ€ (seriously?), the flaw, while potentially a serious problem, was practically little more than a PR headache as the invalid operation that triggered the processor to lock up was never encountered in real-world operations. Additionally, the F0 bug only affected the older Pentium processors, not the Pentium II and Pentium Pro processors Intel was currently shipping at the time. However, the workaround was necessary as malicious software could have exploited the flaw and caused serious problems for PCs and servers using the affected processors.

The RIAA sued Napster causing a judgement against the file-sharing service requiring them to monitor its network for copyright infringing material and restrict access when made aware of such incidents. Napster could not comply with this court order and shut down its service before declaring bankruptcy in 2002. Roxio was the first company to attempt to use the Napster brand for a music service, renaming Pressplay as Napster 2.0. In September 2008, Best Buy purchased the Napster service for $121 million before merging it with the Rhapsody service in December 2011.

It let physicists browse the full text of pre-publication scientific papers on SLAC's SPIRES database directly over the Web. This was a radical improvement over the old system, which involved submitting requests and waiting for fax or email versions to be sent back. As a vital service for the international physics community, the SLAC site became an important early step in helping the World Wide Web live up to its ambitious name.
